{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_fletcher_ver01/data/sn84020645/00517017851/1921031001/0845.xml":{"full_text":"RNING, MARCH 10,1921\nTWELVE PAGES\nNo Occasion For, Sending'\nTroops to. Jackson County\nin \u201cNight Rider\u201d Activities,\nv Declares Governor After,\nTo 1 e p ho n e Conference\nWith Conrad Antiin\nNORMAL CONDITION\nRESUMED, IS REPORT\n\nRaids in Fabios Section Where\nI; \u201cNight Rider\u201d Nests Are\nReported Continue; Total]\nUb\n4; Are Made; Grand Jury In*\ndktments Expected\n:*ir&\nGovernor Thomas E. Kilby\nstated Wednesday that he had not\neven considered the sending of\nstate troops to Jackson county to\nassist in restoring order in that\nsection of the state which has re\ncently been terrorized by \u201cnight\nriders.\u201d\nn\nThe chief executive stated that he\nVas communicated with hr lone dis\ntance telephone, Wedneaday afternoon,\nby Conrad W, Austin, chief of the\nstate law enforcement department, who\n4a now In Jackson county making a\npersonal Investigation of the recent\ndisorders, and that Mr. Austin told him j\nhe S5TV no necessity for the calling of\nstate-troops into service. Such action\non his part, has not even been suggest\ned by anyone, the governor stated, and\nhe was at a loss to know whers rumors\nto the effect that he would probably\ncall Alabama National Guardsmen Into\nService, originated.\nCHATTANOOGA, TBHN* March S\n.V \u2014The excitement under which\nStevenson, Alabama, has heea labor.\nleg for tho past several days an ae\ncent af the aettvttleo of night\nriders has a boat subsided fad nor\nmal coalllof Is about to bo reaek\n\u2022d according to advice* received\nby long distance telephone tonight.\nThe authorities are still conducting\ntheir raids on tftd.Fablus section and\ntoday affected five more arrests on\ncharges of night riding. This makes a\ntotal o\u00a3 27 men who have been Jailed\nsince ths middle of last week, and of\nficers of Jackson county will make\nanother raid tomorrow.\nTho grand Jury has been In special\nsession snd about 100 arrests are ex\npected. Residents of tho cities of\nStevenson snd 8cottsboro who have\nbeen going armed for over a week\nIn fear that the night riders might\nattempt a raid on the Jails to liberate\ntheir companions in crime have become\nconvinced that no such raid is con\ntemplated snd today tns situation, in\nboth towns was Just about as usual,\nwith the exception of ths heavy guards\naround ths Jails.\nFIRES RAGING IN\nFORESTS OF TWO\nCOUNTIES IN STATE\n(Aatodatci Press)\nMOULTON, ALA., March 9\u2014Fir\u00bba are\nraging In the government forest reser\nvation embracing the southern pa ft of\nLawrence county and tho northern\nportion of Winston, hundreds of acres\nbeing swept by the flames.\nM. B. Lufburrow, head of the for\nestry work on the reservation, is .di\nrecting the efforts to control the flres\nat various points In ths two counties,\nand la assisted by planters on farms\nadjaosnt to the reservation.\nSTATE AUTHORIZES\nSCHOOL WARRANT\nj^ptlng under authority of an act of\nthe legislature of 1419, etate auditor\nKltshugh \"Lee, Wedr.eaday, authorized\nthe laauance of a warrant for 97,500\nrepresenting atate aid for the Ninth\nDistrict Agricultural School building\nbeing erected at Blountsville, Ala. The\n-warrant was mail payabld to the board\nof trustees of the new school.\nCYCLONE SUES\nScore of Persons Injured; Monu\nment in Cemetery Leveled\nto Ground\nMACON, MISS. March\ncyclone which atrack several points\nla Noxabee scanty today at 3 p.m.\ntajarcd a score of persons and\neaaaed damage estimated at $25,000.\nPrairie Point, two miles from here,\nwas hit hardest, practically every build\ning in the village being demolished or\ndamaged. The few business houses\nthere were blown down and a number\nof people were hurt, but no deaths\nwere reported. The loss there was\nabout 920,000.\nMacon suffered little damage, but\nthe Macon cemetery, half a mile from\ntown, was swept by the cyclone, monu\nments and markers of the majority of\ngraves being leveled. Ten or twelve\nbuildings, including a few dwellings,\nin the vicinity of the cemetery were\nunroofed. The damage was estimated\nat 99.000.\nMeagre reports reached here of\ndamage at remote-places in the eoun\ntv, but no one was reported killed.\nVl'he cyclone came from a southwester\nly dlrectlo\nWfflRHIT\nSUITE FOR PtYMEIT\nOF UUD IT SHERiH\nf __________\nDeal For Purchase of Site For\ni State Penitentiary From\nCity b Closed by State\nAuditor Wednesday\nIwniN a wamit by the\n\u25a0tat* nlllw Wtlwlay, far fW*\nant ta the cttr Nait(a\u00abrr at\nthe m af 910,000 finally eleeed\n.the transact lea through whloh\nMU acres af the fanner Cany\nSheridan resetlation, upon which\nWUI be laeated tha new at-te prt\naoa, a Baaed treat the posaeaale* af\nthe city af Meatgoasery ta the state\naf Ala Santa. Cyan authority at G.\nB. Reger a. chairman af tha state\nheard at eaatral and economy, tha\nwarrant waa delivered ta WllUtun\nA. Gaater, Jr, Mayer af Moat\ngemcry, after Mayer. Gaater had\nhanded ta Mr. Rogers, etfleial deeda\nta the property.\nThe contribution dt $1,900 made' by\nthe Montgomery Chamber of Commerce\ntoward the .purchase price of the pri\nson' site, has\\ already been delivered to\nthe Montgomery city clerk, it was an\nnounced Wednesday evening.\nChairman Rogers of the state boost\nof control, stated Wednesday, that\nmembers of the board, have definitely\ngodded that the railroad station to\nbe established at the new state peni\ntentiary will bear the name of Kilby,\nAla., In recognition of the fact that the\nconstruction of the new penitentiary\nwas planned by Alabama's present\nchief executive, and that its final estab\nlishment will be due to his foresight\nedness and initiative. The board of\ncontrol will also at a meeting to bo\nheld Thursday, create a new account,\nand to this account whieh will be desig\nnated simply as \u201cKilby\u201d, will be charged\nall expenditures incident to the build\ninf of the prison, glso. the amount paid\nthe -prison site.\nDuring-Thursday's session of the\nboard, at which Martin J. tilde, of\nBirmingham, architect and con-\nstructlon engineer, who Will draw\nUP the plans for the new prison,\nand superintend its building, Mr.\nRogers stated, plans will be made\nlooking to taking up immediately, j\nactual construction work. The\nboard will arrange with Mr. tide\nto make a survey of the site at\nonce and fix upon. a location for\nthe prison building.\nAs soon as this is done, Mr. Rogers\nstates, temporary barracks will be\nconstructed near the prison location,\nand in these barracks will be housed\nthe conviots, who in a large measure\nwill perform all the work Incident to\nthe building of the prison. As soon as\na location is decided upon, Mr. Rogers\nstates, excavations will be begun at\nonce. Mr. Rogers also took occasion\nto repeat the statement originally made\nby Governor Kilby, that all expenses\ninvolved in the building and equipment\nof the prison will be paid by funds de\nrived from the leasing of convict labor.\nWhen Mr. Lide makes his survey of\nthe prison Site property in order to\nlocate the prison building proper, he\nwill also, it is stated, locate sites for\nthe various industrltes which are to\nbe conducted by the state in connec\ntion with the prison. These industries\nif is understood, will include a cotton\nmill, a shoe. factory and an overall\nfactory.\nRUSSIAN JEWISH\nREFUGEES SEEK\nOTHER COUNTRIES\nLONDON, March I\u2014(Jewish Tele\ngraphic Agency)\u2014Reports from Kovno\ntoday say that large numbers of\nJewish refugees from Russia are trying\nto reach the frontiers of Lithuania,\nLatvia and Poland, fearing that the\nuprisings In Russia will result in\nPogroms.\nRepresentatives of the bolshevllcl in\nRiga, have received Instructions from\nMoscow\u00bb not to repatriate any more\nRussians returning from the United\nStates, according to a Riga despatch,\nMARK TWAIN BUST\nFROM IN FRONT OF\nOLD HOME STOLEN\n(Associated Press)\nHARTFORD, CONN, March \u2022_\nTheft of a hast of Saaiael L.\nClemens (Mark Twain) from fa\nfront of the former home of the\nauthor was lefcraed here today.\nThe pedestal of the bast was found\nIn Park river, bat no trace of the\nbast Itself has been discovered.\nA money reward haa been offered\nfor Its retara. aa friends of the\nauthor consider It aa excellent\nlikeness.\nSWITCHMAN KILLED\nAND TWO INJURED\nON COAST LINE\n(Associated Press)\nDOTHAN ALA, March 9\u2014J. M. Huds\npeth. switchman was Instantly killed\nthis afternoon when aa Atlantic Coast\nLiao switch engine and fear ears of\ncoal plunged thirty feet through the\ncoal- chute trestle, and Bob Hubert,\nswitch foreman and Lonnie Blackmon,\nnegro gremlin, were seriously injured.\nThe engineer, who went to the ground\nwith the locomotive was not seriously\nhart.\nS\nPi'\nIS\nPERMIT BEER AND Wl\nBY PRESCRIPTION\nU. S. LAW, RULES\nMJ.\nOpinion by Attornejr&aen\nAlcoholic: Liquors Tor Medical aal\npm; Wheeler Declares Riding Is a\npose of Congress and Prohibition Laws\nBores Congress Should Amend Law\nicfare of AS\n-Beverage Par\nWith Par\n>f States;' Be*\nWAsmwrurt, March 9\u2014Beer and wines are given the same\nstatus as whiskey under an opinion by tlse attojtoey general made\npublic todajvby the bureau of in temal revenue\u00ae\nThe ruling, one of the most i mportaht since'vthe advent of na\ntional prohibition, makes it possible for all alcoholic liquors to be\nused for medical end other non- beverage purposes and for all to\nbe manufactured and sold for th ese purposes subject only to the\nlimitations of the Volstead act on non-bevcragewtoxicants.\nwas wiiu.cn uy lormsr\nattorney General Palmer the day ba-'\nfora be retired from office, and waq la\nreply to a aerlea of questions from In\nternal revenue and prohibition offi\ncials bearing on construction of halt\na dosen moot points In the law.\nWhether'It will upset any regula\ntions of the revenue and enforcement\nbureaus had ndt been determined to\nnight, Commissioner Williams of the\nrevenue bureau, saying he had not had\nan opportunity to study the opinion.\nHe made It public without comment\nand said that ^officials concerned'with\nenforcement would prepare at once to\ndraft regulations carrying out the at\ntorney general's construction of the\ndry law.\nThere were many ranters afloat that\nthe opinion had wrecked plans of dry\nadvocates to obtain restriction of liq\nuor salea Officials refused to comment\non the reports, however, but Wayne 11.\nWheeler, general counsel for the antl\nsaloOn league Issued a statement In\nwhich be said that 39 states had state\ncodes prohibiting the prescribing of\nbeer for medical purposes. Mr. Wheel\ner declared the opinion waa not In ac\ncord with the purpose of the federal\nlaw.\n\u201cCongress clearly did not intend\u2018to\nlegalise what the stale laws prohibit\u201d\nMr. Wheeler said. \u201cUnless the opinion\nIs overruled, congress should amend\nthe law. It Is difficult, of course, to\noverrule It beesuse the government and\nthe brewers sre on the same side of\nthe case and there Is no one to con\ntest It, unless the new stterney gen\neral overrules the ortnlon.\u201d\nThe wlslsm appeared ambigu\nous Is some respects, officials said,\naad as a result they were uuable to\ndeterusAe whether tho government\nhad power 1* the light ef the rul\nlag to limit the number of pro\n\u25a0cnpiiOBi ifaiv* m pajmcuB wmmj\nwrite except tbist tke law specifics.\nae atere tfeaa *plat per pataaa la\na tea tar perltM. Mr. Palace I*-'\ndared be MWmI It' the parpeee\nat ecapreaa t* leave the pbyateiaa\n\u2018-\u25a0\u25a0fettered by pcreraateatal eea\ntrol\u201d ret be tffntbt that repala\ntlcaa alight pgdperly rcatrlet the\namaaat tp^fb a|M aa aaj aaa pre\n\u2022criptlaa. \u2018si\nMr. PalmerVeamd attention to pro*\nvisions of law Witch apparently had\nleft the physiqjaYto act on hta Judg\nment He sugiesjid then that when a\nphysician abuaedt' the privilege he\ncould be dealt gnii| criminally but add\ned that In no eMkiehaald the Judgment\nof the physicians be supplanted by that\nof enforcement! afftotals, a situation\nhe believed w\u00ab\u00bbH result from regu\nlations attempJB to control the use\nof prescrlptlogjFSf\nReplying tb^gjle question whether\nthe governnmjp could restrict the num\nber of permit* Ml manufacture, sell or\nprescribe tn.Atnpj state or community,\nMr. Palmer explained that the Vol\nstead act had limited only tho class\nes to 'which pelmlta could be Issued\nand had permitted no discrimination\nbetween persons within those classes.\nHe said the withholding of permits\ncould not be dott$ legally even though\nofficials were convinced that fewer\npermits prould atifflce In any given\natate or city. 4\nMr. Palmer advised officials that\nthey had \u201campl*1 authority\" to write\nsuch regulations as they believed nec\nessary to. make certain the enforce\nment of the law. Dry advocates stres\nsed this statement, declaring that by n i\nmeans would be found which would j\ncircumvent and handicap the sale of j\nbeer and wines and Would throw open j\nthe door to manufacture of; quantities\nof high alcoholic beer again aa anti- i\nprohibitionists Insisted.\nRay Rnsnton Explains \u201cService\ni s At Cost Plan\u201d on Street Car\n_ m,11\"\"\"1 \u25a0\u00bb'1\nlac AiiuaiuB\npaMUc .wrvfaMMw^wiM.- W\u00abj\nUMday, la cOBaKwln with the pe\nIltlaa of the ttsi\u00ab(Mitr^ Light\n\u25a0U Traction CMpnr far pcmh\n\u00bbla* ta establish eliding etreat\near fare for \u201ceervlee at cost\u201d F.\nC. HaatlHaa, eoaeultlng engineer\naf Suit Orange, Jf. J., athted the\nvalae of the eonpu;'i street rail\nway system when he made hla ap\npraisal at the close of 1930, seas\n\u20222,123,838. He also stated that at\nthat time It weald cost \u20223,737,838\nto replace the street railway. On\n'February 1. of the present year, he\nstated he had appraised the value\nof the street railway property at\n\u20222,117,323 and the cost of replace\nment at \u20222,731,175.\nAfter Mr. Hamilton bad presented\nfigures on the comparative costs ol\noperation of the street car system\nduring the years 1919 and 1920, the\ncommission which had taken up the\nTraction Company\u2019s petition at 11:30\na. m. adjourned until 3 o\u2019clock in the\nafternoon.\nRay Rushton, receiver for the Mont\ngomery Light and Traction Company,\nafter the commission reconvened, next\ntook the stand to testify in support\nof the company's petition. Mr. Rush\nton first told of the Improvements\nwhich have been made In the street\ncar system and In service rendered the\npublic during the past year, stating\nthat further Improvements are con\ntemplated for the near future, includ\ning the installation of new \"turnouts\u20191\non South Court Street, South Law\nrence street, and at other points on\nthe street-car company's lines.\nThe company, he said, has. during\nthe past year done much paving work\non Bell street and elsewhere, adding\nthat thy street car company\u2019s part of\nthe paving work on Cleveland Avenue\nwill amount to something like 990,000.\nHe said that all improvements car\nried out had been made as cheaply as\npossible, and that in his opinion every\ndollar of the quarter of a million dol\ni\u00bbrs Borrowed roy purpose bed\nbeen wisely spang*--\u2014\u00bb>j\nRecalling the occasion upon which1\nhe appeared tefore the eommlsslon to\naak authority to raise street-oar fare* i\nfrom S to 7 cents, Mr, Rushton stated\nthis increase had been ashed In order\nthat the working hours of the \"plat\nform men\u201d might be shortened from\nl] hours to 9 hours. The 7 cent fare, i\nhe said, Just about covered Increases\nin wages granted to street-car motor\nmen and conductors although during\nthe months when traffic was heaviest,\nthere was a little left over.\nMr. Rushton stated that the \u201cplat\nform men\u201d now draw about as much\npay for hours work as they former\nly did for 13 hours, and the result of\nshortening the hours of work had been\nto decrease greatly the number of ac\ncidents and improved the service ren\ndered the public In a remarkable ex\ntent He said that something like 336,\n000 is spent by the company annually\nfor work done In the company's shops\ntoward keeping the cars in good re\npair.\nMr. Raehton stated it was doubt\nful. la his opinion, whether the\neoayia/ eoald mak* aa retar*\nea its lavestwent hy a eoatiaua\ntloa of the 7 rent fare. The only\nway this eoald be daae, he stated,\nwas to leagthes the worklag hoars\nof the esr crews aad reduce their\npay, and he added most emphatic\nally that he did not wish to do\nthft. Asked by Associate Public\nService Conmiuleaer S. P. Gait*,\nlard. If wages paid ta \u201cplatform\nmen\u201d hy the nwntgomery Light\nsad Traction Company are higher\nthaa elsewhere, Mr. Rashtea re\nplied la the negative, statlag they\nage leaa thaa in Birmingham aad\nMobile, hat at the name time wagea\npaid hy the traction company nre\nfair as compared with other cities\nof like sloe.\n\u201cI see no netessity of the Montgom\nery Light and Traction Company re\nmaining In the hands of a receiver,\"\n(Contused Oa Pago Six) j\nBusiness Depression In Europe\nContinues, Say American Consuls\n(Auorlalri Fma)\nWASHINGTON, March e\u2014Ces\ntlaued huatnea Ifprfaiioi la Eu\nropc, with the exception el Italy\nwas reparte4 by American caaaala\nla the moalhly cable aarvcy of\nworld ceoaumlc coadltloas lasaod\ntoday by the department of com\naterce. Signs-ef Improvement were\nscca la the Far Hast bat little\nchaser was aoted ta Booth Amer\nican countries.\nBoth exports sad Imports are de\ncreasing la GredTt Britain, the aar\nvry said, contributing to naem\nploymeat. Payment of heavy -taxes\nwas regraded aa a cause of tlgh\naess la the money market and En\nglish honks were said to have\nleaned two thirds' of their res\nources to finance private eater\nprise.\nKecenb price declines and buslnesi\nstagnation In France, according to the\nsurvey, have tended to strain the cred\nit of banks, several of which were re\nported to be In a difficult position. A\nliquidation of the government owned\nFrench merchant fleet, aggregating\n1,600,000 gross tons, Is being urged lr\nview of the dull period in shipping.\nItalian banks are reporting largt\nprofits, however, the survey contin\nued, and the condition of the govern\nment finances was regarded as non\nfavorable. Local unrest and strike:\nabout Rome have been decreasing bul\nunemployment Is ip evidence It added\nGerman Interests are attempting te\nobtain control of the Austrian govern\nment's former ammunition plants, th.\nsrvey reported and German capita;\nla trying to control the Iran industry\nIn Austria. The general condition o\nV 'ii\nthe Austrian government finances was\nregarded as becoming more favorable\nThe tf8it of living there rose 10 nor\ncent In February, It was reported.\nBusiness depression In Increasing in\nthe Scandinavian countries, the survey\nasserted! while German competition is\nplacing many Industries in a' worse\ncondition than formerly.\nJapan\u2019s foreign trade coatlancd\nthe increase started la January ae\ncording to the- survey while hank\nloans Increased under lower rates\nand easier money. An upward tread\nIn the exchange rate on the United\nStates, It was mi id. Is looked for\nIn Japan. Orders for foreign goods\nare decreasing in China bat the\npresent trade depression la expect\ned to Improve by Jaly, while the\nfinancial situation is already in.\nproving.\nThere has been no Improvement in\nfinancial affairs In Argentina, the sur\nvey said, and bank loans are Increas\ning although deposits are falling off.\nWhile exports are increasing slowly\nImports are dull, the decrease In im\nports from the United States especial\nly becoming more apparent, the sur\nvey said.\nBanks in Brazil are not granting\nloans except for strictly commercial\npurposes the survey continued and de\nposits have been reduced somewhat.\nThe cost of living is increasing stead\nily but large crops are predicted.\nPeru is passing through its read\njustment period without great embar\nasssnent. the survey concluded, gj.\nthough money is tighter and credits\nare more difficult to obtain and no\nrapidity In. the recovery of the ex\nchange rate is expected.\nRailway Development Agents\nof Sonth Hold Convention\nin Montgomery With Jesse\nM. Jones Presiding Over\n|Kw Sessions\nh.i\nA'-,\nCO-OPERATION URGED\nWITH OTHER fORCES\n;\"1',---\nMayor Gunter Welcomes Vm*\nr tor* to City; Advanttfes\nto Bo Derived Through\nPromotion of Better Condi*\ntions Discussed\n\nT\u00bb\u00ab iaftrtiiM* hearty eu-.\n\u2022Kntlom tctmn nHm4> and\nP\u00bbbHo ma the kej note 1 the\nof the Association of Rail.\n**7 Dtrrt\u00bbpa\u00abt A Kent, ml the\nBenth at tke first aesslea of the\nsecond aaaaal meeting erklrk was'\n\u2022Oiled te order yesterday morning\nfa tke aadltorlaai of tke Gay*\nTedlrae Hotel fcy sealer vtce-rres\nIdgat. Jesse M. Jones, general de\nvelopment agent of tke keakoard\nAir Use a .allrood.\nMayor W. A. Ounter, Jr., tn his'usual\nhappy veil), delivered the welcome ad\ndress which was responded to by Mr.\nJones who also delivered tits key-note\nspeech of the meeting. ,ln his talk\nMr. Jones gave the purposes of the as\nsociation as follows:\n\u201c(a) To promote the snctency and\nImportance of Railroad Development\nwork in the South.\n\u201c(b) To bring about an interchange\nof ideas among its members.\n\u201d<o) To co-operate with other or\nganised forces in ths development of\ntha South.\u201d\nIn discussing the benefits to bo de\nrived from tbs work of the develop\nment agents Mr, Jones said:\n\"One of thsi greateat benefits de\nvelopment me\u00bb; of all kinds yonder\n.their respective roads la that of de\nveloping good-will. The reason for\nthis is that real service la render**\ntbh patrons of the line. -ii\n\u2022Thls service is tn promoting better\nAgrleoltural and industrial methods?\nbetter living and production condi\ntions new crops or products, opening\nnew territory. Soliciting and giving\ndata for establishing new Industries,\ncreating better markets, bringing In\ngood citizens from those parts of the\nunion less favored with climate, soil\nand general \u2018it lug conditions, and in\nevery way promoting the welfare of\nall agricultural and industrial patrons\nIn adjacent territory. Tes good-will\nis a valuable asset to a railroad. It\nalways has been needed. Is needed to\nday, and will always bo worth care\nfully guarding.\n\"Tke development agents, of\n\u2022very character, of whatever rail\nway system, have an important\ntask new te perform beeanoe\nthings are net goad on the Paelfle'\nv Coast, In the West, in the Worth,\nor In the Booth. Business restric\ntions are everywhere and In every\nUne. .\u2014mem everywnere are\nstanding an still ae they ess, and\nmy fear Is that they will remain\nthere tee long to protect their fn\ntnre food and feed supply. Their\nrash for gold last year, that did\nnot come, left them unprepared\nfor thla year\u2019s business. The altua\ntlon la weir shown la one Southern\nstate.\n\"It will need thousands of miles of\ncars loaded with grain, hay, potatoes,\neggs, syrup, canned goods, and meat\nproducts, which It could well produco\nItself. The freight It must pay to the\nrailroad on these potential products\nwill be close to $40,000,000. or about\n*140 per farm. The transportation\ncompanies would be far better off If\nthey did not have to carry these com\nmodities, but Instead, the farmer had\nthe money that goes for freight and\nproducts purchased, to put Into per\nmanent investments.\n\"The situation facing industries,\nfinancial and other businesses Ja no\nless out of the normal, jn that the j\niCentinned ea Page Bin)\nBOLSHEV LEADERS I\nESCAPE BY MOTOR\nFROM PETROGRAD\n(AuwMInl rrcmmi\nLONDON. March 9\u2014A despatch to\nthe Londion Times from Riga dated\nWednesday says that all the bolshevik\nleaders In Petrograd escaped by motor\ncars following the capture by the\nrevolutionaries this morning of the en\ntire city, with the exception of the\nNicolai and Finland Railroad stations.\nThe soviet troops suffered heavy losses\nat Krasnoya Selo. 18 miles southeast\nQf Petrograd and at Gatchina, 80 miles\nto the southwest.\nThe Krasnoya Oorko and Oranlen\nbaum fortresses have surrendered. The\nrad army has retreated twenty versits.\nTHE WEATHER\nTHI HUDAV, march is._\nWASHINGTON. March S\u2014(Alabama)\n-\u2014Fair Thursday, cooler la smth \u00bber\nties i Friday fair.\n\u25a0Wednesday witnessed a break In the\nsteady .downpour of sunshine which has\nmade spring seem so near at hand In\nMontgomery. A total of .75 Inches of\nrain fell during the day. between the\nhours of .7:50 and 11:15 and during\nmuch of the rest of the day t^e weath\ner was cloudy, though the sun managed\nto break through again in the after\nnoon. -;a\nThe forecast was for cooler; and\nI cloudy, or partly cloudy weather,\nThursday with a minimum tempera,\nture of 4! to 48 degrees forecasted \"for\nWednesday night.\nWednesday witnessed a remarkably\nslight variation in temperature the\nmaximum for the day being 71 de\ngree! and the minimum 82 degrees.\nGERMANS ORDERED\nSURRENDER ALL\nm4\n.a.\nARMS\n;f\u00a3\nV'\nBelgians Occupy Hambom and Coaling\nPort; German Police in Occupied\ny Towns to Act Under Supervision of\nAllies; Strikes Prohibited in Prd\ndamation of General Degoutte; Ap\nplication of Further Penalties on Ger\nmany Considered at Meeting of Allied\nSupreme Council\n.A\nv A\n*A\nBERLIN, March 9\u2014The Belgians have occupied Hambam, to\nthe north of Duisburg abd the coaling port of the Thyssen work#?\nThe occupation was without incident. Si 1\n'4':\n1 ORDERS SURRENDER 07 ARMS.\nDUESSELDOBF, March 9\u2014General Degoutte\u2019s proclamation\nof-a state of Biegb ordered the s urrender of all arms within 12\nhours and prohibited strikes or sabotage, The German authorities\nand the police are to act pnder s upervision of the allies Street\ntraffic will not be'hindered Unless disturbance* arise.\nALLIED SUPREME COUNCIL MEETS.\nLONDON, Mareh\u2014The allied supreme couneil njpt at the ofR*\ncial residence of the' prime minis teg Mr. Lloyd George, in Down*\nv\u2018w* *v\u00bb.\u00abvmvv rn Asvvf ti*\ning street, this afternoon to eonskier application of the penalties\nto Germany for non-fulfillment o f her reparations obligations.\nThe members of the council took note\nof the fact that the German towns of\nDuesseldorf, Duisburg and Ruhrort had\nbeen occupied Tuesday without inci\ndent and compared notes regarding the\naction to be taken on the second\npenalty, namely, the imposition by\neach allied country of ouch a tax on\nairman imports as it may deem fitting.\nRegarding the third penalty, the\ni conference noted the report of the in\nternational high commission of tha\nRhineland to the effect that the com\nmission had decided by ordinance to\ntake under its orders the customs in\nthe occupied territory and hold the\ncustoms receipts on the frontiers of\nthese territories, placing them in a\nspecial account at the disposal of th*\nreparations commission. i*\nThe dues will for th* present be\nlevied at the German tariff. The high\ncommission is studying the establish\nment of a customs line on tha lthtne.\nCertain other questions were referred\nto the experts who held a meeting this\nafternoon and will present s report to\nthe conference later.\nThe delegates then discussed the\npresent position of the Greeks and\nTurks.\nA bill to give effect to the levying\nof a certain percentage on German Im\nported goods is under consideration by\nthe allied experts. This bill, it is ex\npected, will be introduced in parlia\nment tomorrow and the work of the\nexperts Is almsd at formulating a\n1 plan to be embodied in Similar meas\nures for introduction in the parliaments\nof the other countries.\nBEBUI, March 8\u2014The pahUe la\nthe streets of Berlla outwardly\ngaVe ao indications mf resentment\ntoday over the entente occupation\nof additional territory. Ita conduct t,\nwas eoaspieoonsly In hecplag with\nthe moderation displayed hy edi\ntorial writers, whose comment to\nday showed nnasual reserve aa\ncompared with their oathreoko oa\ntho allien advance lain Germany a\nyear ago.\nCuriosity was the chief symptem of\nthe situation, which as yet is wholly\nan enigma, even the authorities being\nunable to conjecture the scope and\nnature of tho penalties which the en\ntente has threatened to put into opera\ntion.\nTho Reichstag alsq has refused to\nget excited and has* settled down to\nconsideration of the regular calendar.\nIt will recess Thursday to permit the\ncommittee on foreign relations to hold\nan executive session with Dr. Simons,\nthe foreign minister who is expected\nback to Berlin Wednesday night.\nDr. Gustav Stresemann leader of\nt** foopitw party and chairman of the\nforeign relations committee today pro\nnounced the present situation a \"tran\nsltory stage,\" which cannot possibly\ncontinue any length of time, declaring\nit Is bound to prove unprofitable to\nthe entente \u201cunless Frances sole am\nbition centers in the gratMcation of\npolitical aspiration*.\"\nOr. Streacmann predicted that an\nother conference' was bound to suc\nceed tha Luudvn aetioerations. at\nwhich Germany would again be called\nUpon to refuse intolerable and' Infeas\nible conditions. Vj,,\nVorwerts charges that formally arid\nlegally the entente has begun a new\nwar. thus admitting the terms of the\npeace treaty are inadequate and de\nmand revision, snd that' the allies\nthus have Indisputably violated the\ntreaty.\nCuriosity is expressed regarding the\nPart to be'played by fhs American\nsector along the Rhine in' Connection\nwith the prospective^ customs regime,\nalthough It Is acknowledged that this\nspot 1\u00bb not likely to servtfjss \"an opeh\ndoof\" inasmuch a* Gurisarrftood'a dvea'\ntuaiiy would have to find an outlet\nfrom there into France and Belgium.\nWELCOMB ALLIED TROOPS.\n(Associated Preasl\n.DCEtSELDOKi', Merck \u2022\u2014Twenty\nfear hoars have passed stare the allied\ntroops marched Into' the new sese of\noeeapatioa. Not the slightest aatoward\nIncident kss occurred and General Ur\ngent re, ta command at the occupation\nhas retaraed te Mayenee.\n\u201cOne could almost say that our ar\nrival is the fulfillment of a long\ncherished hope.\" commented a high al\nlied officer today.\nTho workers, who might be expected\nto give trouble, show no signs of dis\nsatisfaction. The socialist leaders say\nthe army has promised to respect their\norganisations; that is all they ask. If\nthe army rids them of the hated\n\u201cgreen devils,\" as the state police are\ncalled^ they' promise to live on the\nbeet terms with it.\nAt Duisburg and Ruhrort a certain\nferment is apparent. The walls are\nplastered with placards headed 'With\nthe red flag. The soldiers had occas\nionally to disperse sullen featured\ngroups, but It seems merely a passing\nshow of ill humor, for the factories\nare working full blast, while other\nsections of the population appear to\nreel relief\nThe occupation assures the mainten\nance of that order so dear to the Ger\nman heart, while General Degoutte'y\nproclamation promising a better food\nsupply has made an excellent iljr\npression. e\nFINAL SlKlKb 5L i ILLMbNl\n,IS EXPECTED ON SATURDAY\ni Gtmtw Tkonai E, Kilby atMM\nWHIanlar (kit be will\nuncc hla ,\"**1\nMltlmnit af tM Alabama ml\n\u25a0trike, la which he ha* been uaei\neele arbiter at eihtlu dlffereaees\nbetweeat the eeal aperatars and\nminers, aatll he has given thorough\nconsideration ta the report at his\naersoaal represea tot Ives, appelate*\nby hlat ta make accessary laves ti\nps t leas. It ta expected thla repeat'\nwill ha filed with the chief exeea\ntlve name time Tharaday, aad H\nwill prabahly he Saturday befare\nhe la able ta aaaaaace his flaal\ndeetalea.\nFrom 10:10 o'clock Wednesday morn\ning until long after the noon hour,\nthe governor\u2019s personal representatives\nwere In conference with him In his\nprivate office at the state capital con\ncerning certain points touched upon by\nmembers of tha committee In conduct\ning their investigations. It had pre\nviousiy been announced by member^\nof the committee that they would ooa*\nfer informally with the governor betdre\ncompiling their formal report.\nAt 2 o\u2019clock, members of the commit*\ntee, Capt. William T. Sheehan, John\nW. Durr, and Rickard M. Hobble, met\nin /he Montgomery Chamber of CotA\nmerce consultation rooms and' began\nthe preparation of their report SJttl\nrecommendations which will be pro*\n\u25a0anted to Governor Kilby as soon asf\nthey are completed. Except for a few.\nminutes recess for supper, the gover\nnor's representatives remained In .ar-..\neion until 10 o'clock, Wednesday night,\nbeing SLBSisted in their work by Wil\nliam F. Black, secretary of tbe Cham\nber of Commerce, who also acted as\nsecretary to the committee of repre\nsentatives during their stay in Birm\ningham.\nIt* was stated by members of the\ncommittee that they did not expect 4\u00bb\ncomplete their report unll Thursday,\nor possibly Friday.\n'Mi\nACREAGE OF WHEAT\nIN FRANCE SHOWS\nINCREASE IN 1921\n(AawUlnl Frew)\nWASHINGTON, March 9\u2014The total\narea town to wheat in France tor the\nmi harvest waa 13,131,000 acres, or an\nincrease of percent over last year\nand 3.3 percent over the preceding\nyears\u2019 average, according to a report\nto the department of agriculture today\nfrom the International Institute of\nAgriculture at Rome. The area sown\nto rye showed an Increase of 4:7 per*\ncent over the preceding year and to\noats a little less than one percent.\nIn British India the area sown to\nwheat for the next harvest was 33,\n333.000 acres, or 23 percent below the\n1920 area, while the wheat area for\nBulgaria was about one percent greater\nthan for the preceding year.\nCALEB POWERS IS\nSUED FOR DIVORCE;\nCRUELTY CHARGED\n(AomUM Pma) ''S\nWASHINQTON, March 9\u2014Caleb Pow.\ner% a former member of congress^\nwhoso trials in connection with the\nkilling of former Governor Goebel, of\nKentucky, some years ago attracted\nnation-wide attention, was sued here\ntoday by his wife, Anna M. D. Towers\nfor. limited dlyorce, \u25a0the petition, died\nin, the District of Columbia supreme\ncourt, charged cruelty and non-sup\nport. j\nJuetioe Stafford Issued a rule\nagainst the defendant, who now live*\nin Washington, to show cause on\nMarch IS why he should not be r*\u00bb\nquired.10 pay temporary alimony pend*\nin* t> outcome of tha proceedings\njf\nf","height":"27736","width":"20020"}}
